Normally Id copy the data dictionary, but its formatting poorly for the purpose at the moment. The only solution is to simply use the one on the site. Anyway, lets look at things. There are five datasets: key_crop_yields, fertilizer, tractors, land_use, and arable_land.

key_crop_yields: Contains data on countries, continents, and regions. The unit of observation appears to be the geographic location and year. To get only countries, exclude rows where is.na(code) is true. For each country/year, there are observations for the crop yield, crops including things like wheat, rice, maize, and so on. The unit is tonnes per hectare, which means the data is already fairly relative.

fertilizer: Again, country/year is the unit of observation. The variables include cereal yield in tonnes per hectare and nitrogen fertilizer use in kilograms per hectare.

tractors: Same unit; variables are tractors per 100 sq km arable land, cereal yield in kg per hectare, and total population according to Gapminder.

land_use: Variables include cereal yield index, change to land area used for cereal production since 1961, and again total population via Gapminder.

arable_land: A single variable: arable land needed to produce a fixed quantity of crops (1.0 = 1961).

Since these datasets all have the same unit of observation, I can merge them if I want. But if I dont thats probably okay too. Lets do some skimming.

Merging didnt go poorly, but it didnt go well. Some of the years are given with a BC suffix, which presents obvious problems. This data is interesting, but Im not sure how they calculated it. Consequently, most of the year variables can be ignored. Im not sure how it handled year vairables when the value was NA. I guess it merged no matter what because it was uniquely identified with a country and an NA, but thats not true is it. Whether or not its useful to merge these remains to be seen. Probably it is not as useful as using them in their native forms.

Agh ggflags has to be installed from source, which doesnt work because of that stupid apostrophe in my file path. No flags then, I guess. I guess I could clone the repo on my dev account and compile it manually, like I do when I make my own packages. This is what I did. Lets see if it worked.
